'' || .500 || .000 || .167 || '''16.0''' || .7 || '''2.0''' || '''1.3''' || 8.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1995 NBA playoffs|1995]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1994\u201395 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio]]\n| 14 || 12 || 32.8 || .542 || .000 || .571 || 14.8 || 1.3 || .9 || .0 || '''8.9'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#afe6ba;\"|[[1996 NBA playoffs|1996]]\u2020\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1995\u201396 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| 18 || 15 || 34.4 || .485 || {{sort|-|\u2014}} || .593 || 13.7 || '''2.1''' || .8 || .4 || 7.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#afe6ba;\"|[[1997 NBA playoffs|1997]]\u2020\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1996\u201397 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| 19 || 14 || 28.2 || .370 || '''.250''' || .577 || 8.4 || 1.4 || .5 || .2 || 4.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#afe6ba;\"|[[1998 NBA playoffs|1998]]\u2020\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1997\u201398 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| 21 || 9 || 34.4 || .371 || '''.250''' || .605 || 11.8 || 2.0 || .7 || .6 || 4.9\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Career\n| 169 || 89 || 28.3 || .490 || .149 || .540 || 9.9 || 1.2 || .6 || .6 || 6.4\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Awards, records, and achievements==\n{{main|List of career achievements by Dennis Rodman}}\n\n==Legacy in basketball==\nFrom the beginning of his career Rodman was known for his defensive hustle, which was later accompanied by his rebounding prowess. In Detroit, he was mainly played as a [[small forward]], and his usual assignment was to neutralize the opponent's best player; Rodman was so versatile that he could guard centers, forwards, or guards equally well<ref name=\"nbacom\" /> and won two [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award]]s. From 1991 on, he established himself as one of the best rebounders of all time, averaging at least 15 rebounds per game in six of the next seven years.<ref name=\"stats\" /> Playing [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]] as member of the Spurs and the Bulls, he had a historical outburst in the [[1996 NBA Finals]]: he twice snared 11 offensive rebounds, equalling an all-time NBA record. In addition, he had a career-high 34-rebound game on March 4, 1992.<ref name=\"singlegamerebounds\">{{cite web |title=NBA Single Game Leaders and Records for Total Rebounds |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/leaders/trb_game.html |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 11, 2008}}</ref> Rodman's rebounding prowess with Detroit and San Antonio was also aided by his decreased attention to defensive positioning and helping teammates on defense.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schmitz|first=Brian|title=Hill and Spurs have hardly felt Rodman's loss|date=March 31, 1996|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|page=5D|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_aZhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UI4DAAAAIBAJ&dq=rodman%20rotate%20spurs%20defense&pg=6550%2C6191428|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"halberstam\">{{cite book|last=Halberstam|first=Dave|title=Playing for Keeps: Michael Jordan and the World He Made|year=2012|publisher=Open Road Media|isbn=9781453286142|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QnAG5M8lpm4C&pg=PT357&dq=rodman+rebound+defense+help#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=February 22, 2013|quote=He'll cheat a little bit on his positioning on defense in order to get his rebounds.}}</ref><ref name=\"simmons_book\">{{cite book|last=Simmons|first=Bill|title=The Book of Basketball: The NBA According to The Sports Guy|page=[https://archive.org/details/bookofbasketball00simm/page/327 327]|year=2009|publisher=ESPN Books|isbn=978-0-345-51176-8|url=https://archive.org/details/bookofbasketball00simm/page/327}}</ref> Daly said Rodman was selfish about rebounding, but deemed him a hard worker and coachable.<ref name=\"halberstam\" /> Rodman's defensive intensity returned while with Chicago.<ref name=\"simmons_book\" />\n\nOn offense, Rodman's output was mediocre. He averaged 11.6 points per game in his second season, but his average steadily dropped: in the three championship seasons with the Bulls, he averaged five points per game and connected on less than half of his field goal attempts.<ref name=\"stats\" /> His free throw shooting (lifetime average: .584) was considered a big liability: on December 29, 1997, [[Bubba Wells]] of the [[Dallas Mavericks]] committed six intentional fouls against him in only three minutes, setting the record for the fastest foul out in NBA history. The intention was to force him to attempt free throws, which in theory would mean frequent misses and easy ball possession without giving up too many points. However, this plan backfired, as Rodman hit 9 of the 12 attempts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fischer |first1=David |title=Take My Record, Please |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/15/sports/take-my-record-please.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=September 11, 2008 |date=May 15, 2005}}</ref> This was Dallas coach [[Don Nelson]]'s early version of what would later develop into the famous \"[[Hack-a-Shaq]]\" method that would be implemented against [[Shaquille O'Neal]], [[Dwight Howard]], and other poor free throw shooters.\n\nIn 14 NBA seasons, Rodman played in 911 games, scored 6,683 points, and grabbed 11,954 rebounds, translating to 7.3 points and 13.1 rebounds per game in only 31.7 minutes played per game.<ref name=\"stats\" /><ref name=\"rebleader\" /> NBA.com lauds Rodman as \"arguably the best rebounding forward in NBA history and one of the most recognized athletes in the world\" but adds \"enigmatic and individualistic, Rodman has caught the public eye for his ever-changing hair color, tattoos and, unorthodox lifestyle\".<ref name=\"nbacom\" /> On the hardwood, he was recognized as one of the most successful defensive players ever, winning the NBA championship five times in six NBA Finals appearances (1989, 1990, 1996\u20131998; only loss 1988), being crowned [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|NBA Defensive Player of the Year]] twice (1990\u20131991) and making seven NBA All-Defensive First Teams (1989\u20131993, 1995\u20131996) and NBA All-Defensive Second Teams (1994). He additionally made two All-NBA Third Teams (1992, 1995), two NBA All-Star Teams (1990, 1992) and won seven straight rebounding crowns (1992\u20131998) and finally led the league once in field goal percentage (1989).<ref name=\"stats\" />\n\nRodman was recognized as the prototype bizarre player, stunning basketball fans with his artificial hair colors, numerous tattoos and body piercings, multiple verbal and physical assaults on officials, frequent ejections, and his tumultuous private life.<ref name=\"nbacom\" /> He was ranked No. 48 on the 2009 revision of ''[[SLAM Magazine]]''{{'}}s Top 50 Players of All-Time.<ref>\"We Got 50!\", ''Slam Magazine'', August 2009</ref> [[Metta World Peace]] played one year with the 91 jersey number in homage to Rodman, who he described as a player who he liked \"on the court as a hustler, not when he kicked the cameraman.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=NBA: 24\u2013second clock |url=https://www.deseret.com/2004/11/1/19858701/nba-24-151-second-clock |website=Deseret News |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=November 1, 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name = Dennis Rodman\n| image =\n| birth_name = Dennis Keith Rodman\n| children = 3\n| spouse = Annie Bakes (divorced)<br>{{marriage|[[Carmen Electra]]|November 1998|April 1999|reason=div}}<br>{{marriage|Michelle Moyer|May 13, 2003|2012|reason=div}}\n| caption =\n| names = Impostor [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]]<br>Dennis Rodman\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=7}}\n| weight = {{convert|220|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| family = Shirley Rodman (mother)<br>Philander Rodman Jr. (father)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|5|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Trenton, New Jersey]]\n| resides =\n| billed = [[Chicago, Illinois]]<br>[[Los Angeles, California]]\n| trainer =\n| debut = March 10, 1997<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/d/dennis-rodman.html|title=Dennis Rodman|publisher=}}</ref>\n| retired = 2000 (first retirement)<br>2008 (second retirement)\n}}\n\n===World Championship Wrestling (1997\u20131999)===\n{{Main|New World Order (professional wrestling)|l1=New World Order (nWo)}}\nRodman took up his hobby of professional wrestling seriously and appeared on the edition of March 10 of ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Monday Nitro]]'' with his friend [[Hulk Hogan|Hollywood Hulk Hogan]] in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW). At the March 1997 [[Uncensored 1997|Uncensored]] event, he appeared as a member of the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo]]. His first match was at the July 1997 [[Bash at the Beach (1997)|Bash at the Beach]] event, where he teamed with Hogan in a loss to [[Lex Luger]] and [[Big Show|The Giant]].<ref name=\"interbasket\" /> At the August 1997 [[Road Wild 1997|Road Wild]] event, Rodman appeared as the Impostor [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]] hitting Luger with a baseball bat to help Hogan win the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]].\n\nAfter the [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u201398 season]], where Rodman and the [[Chicago Bulls]] defeated [[Karl Malone]] and the [[Utah Jazz]] in the [[1998 NBA Finals]], Rodman and Malone squared off again, this time in a tag team match at the July 1998 [[Bash at the Beach (1998)|Bash at the Beach]] event. He fought alongside [[Hulk Hogan]], and Malone tagged along with [[Diamond Dallas Page]]. In a poorly received match, the two power forwards exchanged \"rudimentary headlocks, slams and clotheslines\" for 23 minutes. Rodman bested Malone again as he and Hogan picked up the win.<ref name=\"bash1998\">{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alex |title=Remembering When the Rodman-Malone NBA Finals Feud in 1998 Led to a WCW Match |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2771950-remembering-when-the-rodman-malone-nba-finals-feud-in-1998-led-to-a-wcw-match |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=June 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRodman returned to [[WCW]] in 1999 and feuded with [[Randy Savage]]. This culminated in a match at [[Road Wild (1999)|Road Wild]] which Rodman lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/roadwild.html#99|title=Road Wild 1999 results|accessdate=Sep 24, 2016|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments}}</ref>\n\n===i-Generation Superstars of Wrestling and retirement (2000)===\nOn July 30, 2000, Rodman competed on the [[i-Generation Superstars of Wrestling]] Rodman Down Under{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} pay-per-view event. He fought against i-Generation champion [[Curt Hennig]] in an [[Professional Wrestling Death match|Australian Outback match]]; Hennig won the match by disqualification. Following the match, Rodman refrained from wrestling at the top level and retired.<ref name=\"top10\" />\n\n===Hulk Hogan's Celebrity Championship Wrestling (2008)===\nRodman came out of retirement to appear as a contestant on ''[[Hulk Hogan]]'s [[Hulk Hogan's Celebrity Championship Wrestling|Celebrity Championship Wrestling]]'', broadcast on [[Country Music Television|CMT]]. Rodman was the winner of the series, defeating other challengers such as [[Eric Esch|Butterbean]] and [[Dustin Diamond]].\n\n===Championships and accomplishments===\n* '''[[Hulk Hogan's Celebrity Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** Celebrity Championship Wrestling tournament\n\n==Media appearances==\n[[File:Trump and Rodman 2009.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Rodman with [[Donald Trump]] for ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 8)|Celebrity Apprentice]]'']]\nIn 1996, Rodman had his own MTV reality talk show called ''[[The Rodman World Tour]]'', which featured him in a series of odd-ball situations.<ref>Mukherjee, Tiarra. [https://ew.com/ew/article/0,,294070,00.html Raging Bull]. ''Entertainment Weekly'', 1996, Retrieved August 31, 2008</ref> That same year, Rodman had two appearances in releases by rock band [[Pearl Jam]]. A Polaroid picture of Rodman's eyeball is on the cover of the album ''[[No Code]]'', and \"Black, Red, Yellow\", B-side of its lead single \"[[Hail, Hail]]\", was written about Rodman and has him contribute a voice message.<ref>Blistein, John. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-dennis-rodman-cradle-eddie-vedder-during-chicago-show-w435864 Watch Dennis Rodman Cradle Eddie Vedder During Chicago Show]. ''Rolling Stone'', 2016, Retrieved August 31, 2018</ref>\n\nA year later, he made his feature film debut in the action film ''[[Double Team (film)|Double Team]]'' alongside [[Jean-Claude Van Damme]] and [[Mickey Rourke]]. The film was critically panned and his performance earned him three [[Golden Raspberry Award]]s: Worst New Star, Worst Supporting Actor and Worst Screen Couple (shared with Van Damme).{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Rodman starred in ''[[Simon Sez]]'', a 1999 action/comedy and co-starred with [[Tom Berenger]] in a 2000 action film about skydiving titled ''[[Cutaway (2000 film)|Cutaway]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |title=Dennis Rodman |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0005379/ |website=IMDb |accessdate=August 31, 2008}}</ref> In 1998, he joined the cast of the syndicated TV show ''Special Ops Force'', playing 'Deke' Reynolds, a flamboyant but skilled ex-Army helo pilot and demolitions expert.\n\nIn 2005, Rodman became the first man to pose naked for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]]'s advertisement campaign \"Rather Go Naked Than Wear Fur\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Rodman To Strip For Peta |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/dennis-rodman/news/rodman-to-strip-for-peta |website=Contactmusic.com |accessdate=August 31, 2008 |date=December 22, 2004}}</ref> That same year, Rodman traveled to Finland, at first, he was present at [[Sonkaj\u00e4rvi]] in July in a [[wife-carrying]] contest. However, he resigned from the contest due to health problems.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Caple |first1=Jim |title=The amazing race |url=https://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story?page=caple/europe/050706 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=August 31, 2008}}</ref> Also in 2005, Rodman published his second autobiography, ''I Should Be Dead By Now''; he promoted the book by sitting in a [[coffin]].<ref name=\"top10\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />\n\nRodman became Commissioner of the [[Lingerie Football League]] in 2005.<ref name=\"top10\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated34\" />\n\nSince his initial entry into acting, he has appeared in few acting roles outside of playing himself. Rodman has made an appearance in an episode of ''[[3rd Rock from the Sun]]'' playing the character of himself, except being a fellow alien with the Solomon family.<ref name=\"imdb\" /> He voiced an animated version of himself in the ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Treehouse of Horror XVI]]\".\n\nRodman has also appeared in several reality shows: in January 2006, Rodman appeared on the [[Celebrity Big Brother 2006 (UK)|fourth version]] of ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (UK)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' in the UK, and on July 26, 2006, in the UK series ''[[Love Island (2005 TV series)|Love Island]]'' as a houseguest contracted to stay for a week.<ref name=\"imdb\" /> Finally, he appeared on the show ''[[The Mole (U.S. Season 4)|Celebrity Mole]]'' on ABC. He wound up winning the $222,000 grand prize.<ref>{{cite web |title=Angie Everhart revealed as 'Celebrity Mole Yucatan' mole while Dennis Rodman wins $222,000 |url=https://www.realitytvworld.com/news/angie-everhart-revealed-as-celebrity-mole-yucatan-mole-while-dennis-rodman-wins-222000-2282.php |website=Reality TV World |accessdate=August 31, 2008 |date=February 19, 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Rodman joined as a spokesman for a sports website OPENSports.com, the brainchild of [[Mike Levy]], founder and former CEO of [[CBSSports.com|CBS Sportsline.com]]. Rodman also writes a blog and occasionally answers members' questions for OPEN Sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emediawire.com/releases/2008/11/emw1630124.htm |title=Basketball's Ultimate Bad-Boy Dennis Rodman Announces Partnership With OPEN Sports |accessdate=March 6, 2009 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602221711/http://www.emediawire.com/releases/2008/11/emw1630124.htm |archivedate=June 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he appeared as a contestant on ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 8)|Celebrity Apprentice]]''. Throughout the season, each celebrity raised money for a charity of their choice; Rodman selected the [[Court Appointed Special Advocate]]s of [[New Orleans]]. He was the fifth contestant eliminated, on March 29, 2009.\n\nIn 2013, he appeared again as a contestant on ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 13)|Celebrity Apprentice]]''. He raised $20,000 for the [[Make-A-Wish Foundation]] and was the sixth contestant eliminated, on April 7, 2013.\n\nIn March 2013, Rodman arrived at the [[Vatican City]] during voting in the [[papal conclave, 2013|papal conclave]] for the selection of a new pope.<ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/13/dennis-rodman-vatican-papal-conclave|title=Dennis Rodman at the Vatican: 'I want to be anywhere in the world I'm needed'|first=Paul|last=Owen|date=March 13, 2013|website=the Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated34\" /> The trip was organized by an Irish gambling company. \"I'm just promoting this website. It's a gambling website, and it's about people who are going to bet on the new pope, and if he's black, you get your money back\", said Rodman.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2292818/Dennis-Rodman-arrives-Vatican-latest-publicity-stunt-promoting-black-cardinal-gambling-website.html|title=Dennis Rodman arrives at the Vatican in latest publicity stunt promoting first black cardinal and a gambling website|work=Daily Mail|last=Golgowski|first=Nina|date=March 13, 2013|accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Rodman joined Premier Brands to launch and promote Bad Boy Vodka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/eats/nba-star-dennis-rodman-launch-bad-boy-vodka-brand-article-1.1397237|title=Former NBA star Dennis Rodman to launch his own Bad Boy Vodka brand|first=Jeanette|last=Settembre|publisher=NY Daily News}}</ref>\n\nRodman's visits to North Korea were depicted in the 2015 documentary film ''[[Dennis Rodman's Big Bang in Pyongyang]]''.<ref name=\"Personally\">{{cite web |url=https://www.personallyspeakingbureau.com/speaker/matt-cooper-broadcaster-journalist-and-biographer-of-tony-oreilly/|title=Matt Cooper Broadcaster, Journalist, and biographer of Tony O'Reilly|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Rodman was featured on the alternative R&B/hip-hop duo [[Mansionz]] self-titled album ''[[Mansionz (album)|Mansionz]]''. He provides vocals on the single \"Dennis Rodman\" and uncredited vocals on \"i'm thinking about horses\".\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Family===\nRodman's first wife was Annie Bakes,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> with whom he had a daughter named Alexis (born 1988).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref name=\"ChicagoTribuneDec1988\">{{cite news|last=Howard|first=Johnette|title=Believe It: Dennis Rodman's Improbable Life Story|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1988-12-18/sports/8802250710_1_dennis-rodman-junior-college-basketball-ekg/3|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=December 18, 1988}}</ref> They divorced in the early 1990s.<ref name=\"annie\" /> Rodman married model [[Carmen Electra]] in November 1998 at the [[Little Chapel of the Flowers]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref name=\"Rodman and Electra\">{{cite web |title=15 years ago, Carmen Electra and Dennis Rodman got married in Las Vegas |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2013/11/15-years-ago-carmen-electra-and-dennis-rodman-got-married-in-las-vegas |website=For The Win |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=November 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Walls |first1=Jeannette |title=Rodman says Electra never got over him |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/rodman-says-electra-never-got-over-him-wbna13639813 |website=TODAY.com |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=August 2, 2006}}</ref> Electra filed for divorce in March 1999.<ref name=\"Rodman and Electra\" />\n\nIn 1999 Rodman met Michelle Moyer, with whom he had a son, Dennis Jr. (\"D. J.\", born 2000)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://usatodayhss.com/2017/dennis-rodman-jr-transferring-to-jserra-per-now-former-coach|title=Dennis Rodman Jr. transferring to JSerra, per now former coach|date=September 27, 2017|work=USA TODAY High School Sports|access-date=May 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and a daughter, Trinity (born 2001). Moyer and Rodman married in 2003 on his 42nd birthday.<ref>Haldane, David. [https://articles.latimes.com/2003/may/14/local/me-rodman14 \"Rodman Celebrates His Birthday With a Wedding\"]. ''Los Angeles Times''. May 14, 2003. Retrieved August 31, 2008</ref> Michelle Rodman filed for divorce in 2004, although the couple spent several years attempting to reconcile. The marriage was officially dissolved in 2012, when Michelle again petitioned the court to grant a divorce. It was reported that Rodman owed $860,376 in child and spousal support.<ref name=\"support\">{{cite web|url=https://latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0328-dennis-rodman-20120328,0,6144244.story|title=Dennis Rodman could face jail over child and spousal support|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 28, 2012|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRodman's son D. J. started playing college basketball for [[Washington State Cougars men's basketball|Washington State]] in 2019. His sister, Trinity, signed to play for the [[Washington State Cougars women's soccer|Cougars women's soccer team]] starting in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawson|first=Theo|title=WSU soccer signs top-ranked forward Trinity Rodman, daughter of ex-NBA superstar|date=December 17, 2019|work=The Spokesman-Review|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/wsu-cougars/wsu-soccer-signs-top-ranked-forward-trinity-rodman-daughter-of-ex-nba-superstar/|accessdate=January 5, 2020|via=SeattleTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Alcohol issues===\nRodman entered an outpatient rehab center in Florida in May 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20197923,00.html |title=Dennis Rodman Enters Rehab |author=Brian Orloff |date=May 5, 2008 |work=People |accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> In May 2009, his behavior on [[The Apprentice (U.S. season 8)|''Celebrity Apprentice'']] led to an intervention which included [[Phil Jackson]] as well as Rodman's family and other friends. Rodman initially refused to enter rehabilitation because he wanted to attend the ''Celebrity Apprentice'' reunion show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b121941_dennis_rodman_rebounds_back_rehab.html |title=Dennis Rodman Rebound Back to Rehab |author=Megan Masters, Aly Weisman |date=May 3, 2008 |publisher=E! Online |accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollyscoop.com/dennis-rodman/dennis-rodman-checks-into-rehab_20122.aspx|title=Dennis Rodman Checks Into Rehab|author=Ani Esmailian|publisher=Hollyscoop|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> In 2009, Rodman agreed to appear on the third season of ''[[Celebrity Rehab with Dr. Drew]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/dennis-rodman-mindy-mccready-sign-on-for-celebrity-rehab-200916|title =Dennis Rodman, Mindy McCready Sign On for ''Celebrity Rehab''|date=June 1, 2009|publisher=Us Weekly|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-briefs.ew.com/2009/06/01/vh1-announces-n/|title=VH1 announces new cast for third season of ''Celebrity Rehab''|author=Tim Stack|date=June 1, 2009|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> Rodman remained a patient at the Pasadena Recovery Center for the 21-day treatment cycle. A week after completion he entered a sober-living facility in the Hollywood Hills, which was filmed for the second season of ''[[Sober House]]''. During episode seven of ''Sober House'', Rodman was shown being reunited with his mother Shirley, from whom he had been estranged for seven years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/video/misc/507111/denniss-reconnection.jhtml#id=1637415|title=\"Dennis's Reconnection\" Show Clip|publisher=VH1|date=April 23, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426142744/http://www.vh1.com/video/misc/507111/denniss-reconnection.jhtml#id=1637415|archivedate=April 26, 2010}}</ref> During this same visit Shirley also met Rodman's two children for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/video/sober-house-with-dr-drew/full-episodes/episode-7/1637586/playlist.jhtml |title=Shirley Rodman meets Dennis Rodman's children for first time (at minute mark 26:00) |publisher=VH1 |date=April 23, 2010 |accessdate=April 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903134405/http://www.vh1.com/video/sober-house-with-dr-drew/full-episodes/episode-7/1637586/playlist.jhtml |archivedate=September 3, 2011}}</ref> On January 10, 2010, on the same day that ''Celebrity Rehab'' premiered, Rodman was removed from an Orange County, California restaurant for disruptive behavior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tmz.com/2010/01/10/dennis-rodman-celebrity-rehab-irvine-cops/|title=Boozy Dennis Rodman Booted from Restaurant|date=January 10, 2010|publisher=TMZ|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> In March 2012, Rodman's financial advisor said, \"In all honesty, Dennis, although a very sweet person, is an alcoholic. His sickness impacts his ability to get work.\"<ref name=\"alcohol\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31751_162-57405718-10391697/dennis-rodman-in-debt-faces-possible-jail-time/|title=Dennis Rodman in debt, faces possible jail time|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=March 28, 2012|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 15, 2014, Rodman again entered a rehabilitation facility to seek treatment for alcohol abuse. This came on the heels of a well-publicized trip to [[North Korea]] where his agent, Darren Prince, reported he had been drinking heavily and to an extent \"that none of us had seen before.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Forrest |first=Steve |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/18/us/dennis-rodman-rehab/ |title=Dennis Rodman checks into alcohol rehab after N. Korea trip |publisher=CNN |date=January 19, 2014 |accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legal troubles===\nOn November 5, 1999, Rodman and his then-wife, [[Carmen Electra]], were charged with misdemeanors after police were notified of a domestic disturbance. Each posted a bail worth $2,500 and were released with a temporary restraining order placed on them.<ref>{{cite web|title= Dennis Rodman Arrested for Fighting With His Wife|author= Charles Montaldo|url= http://crime.about.com/od/famousdiduno/ig/celebrity_mugshots/rodmandennis.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1999, Rodman was arrested for drunk driving and driving without a valid driver's license. In July 2000, Rodman pleaded guilty to both charges and was ordered to pay $2,000 in fines as well as attend a three-month treatment program.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/07/18/sports/main216457.shtml|title=Rodman Pleads Guilty To DUI|date=July 18, 2000|publisher=cbsnews.com|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, he was arrested for interfering with police investigating a code violation at a restaurant he owned; the charges were eventually dropped.<ref name=\"rebound\" /> After settling down in [[Newport Beach, California]], the police appeared over 70 times at his home because of loud parties.<ref name=\"rebound\" /> In early 2003, Rodman was arrested and charged with domestic violence at his home in Newport Beach for allegedly assaulting his then-fianc\u00e9e.<ref>{{cite news|title= Dennis Rodman arrested in L.A.|accessdate= May 1, 2008|url= http://ca.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idCAN0143922820080501 | agency=Reuters|date=May 1, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Rodman pleaded [[nolo contendere]] to [[drunk driving]] in [[Las Vegas]]. He was fined $1,000 and ordered to serve 30 days of [[home detention]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2004-04-21-rodman-dui_x.htm|title=Dennis Rodman pleads no contest to DUI|accessdate=January 24, 2010|work=USA Today|date=April 21, 2004}}</ref> On April 30, 2008, Rodman was arrested following a [[domestic violence]] incident at a Los Angeles hotel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Police arrest Rodman after report of dispute at hotel |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/news/story?id=3376837 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=August 31, 2008 |date=May 1, 2008}}</ref> On June 24, 2008, he pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] to the misdemeanor spousal battery charges. He received three years of [[probation]] and was ordered to undergo one year of domestic violence [[List of counseling topics|counseling]] as well as 45 hours of [[community service]], which were to involve some physical labor activities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dennis Rodman Pleads No Contest in Domestic Assault |url=https://people.com/crime/dennis-rodman-pleads-no-contest-in-domestic-assault/ |website=PEOPLE.com |accessdate=August 31, 2008 |date=June 25, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/sns-ap-bkn-rodman-plea,0,3774760.story | title=Rodman pleads no contest to spousal battery | agency=Associated Press | work=Chicago Tribune | date=June 25, 2008 | accessdate=June 25, 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627161953/http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/sns-ap-bkn-rodman-plea,0,3774760.story | archivedate=June 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn November 21, 2016, Rodman was charged with causing a [[hit and run]] accident, lying to police, and driving without a license following an incident on [[Interstate 5]] near [[Santa Ana, California]], in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-dennis-rodman-charged-20161121-story.html |title=Dennis Rodman facing criminal charges in July hit-and-run, prosecutors say |publisher=LA Times |date= |accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that Newport Beach yoga studio owner Ali Shah accused Rodman of helping steal over $3,500 worth of items from the studio's reception area, including a 400-pound decorative geode. Rodman disputed the account, claiming the owner told him \"Dennis, get anything you want.\" No charges had been filed at the time of reporting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/socal/daily-pilot/news/tn-dpt-me-nb-yoga-studio-theft-20190510-story.html |title=Newport Beach yoga studio alleges Dennis Rodman and others stole clothing and a 400-pound crystal |publisher=LA Times |date= |accessdate=May 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2019, Rodman was charged with misdemeanor battery after slapping a man at the Buddha Sky Bar in Delray Beach, Florida.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dennis Rodman Charged with Battery for Allegedly Slapping Man at Bar |url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/10/18/dennis-rodman-charged-battery-slapping-man-bar/ |publisher=TMZ |accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nOn July 24, 2015, Rodman publicly endorsed [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]]. That same month, Rodman sent out an [[List of Donald Trump presidential campaign endorsements, 2016|endorsement]] tweet, stating, \"Donald Trump has been a great friend for many years. We don't need another politician, we need a businessman like Mr. Trump! Trump 2016.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/24/politics/dennis-rodman-donald-trump-endorsement/index.html|title=Dennis Rodman endorses Trump for president |accessdate=September 17, 2016|work=CNN |location=New York City |first=Sophie|last=Tatum|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> Rodman and then U.S. Presidential hopeful [[Donald Trump|Trump]] had previously appeared together on ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 8)|Celebrity Apprentice]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lerner|first1=Adam B.|title=Dennis Rodman endorses Donald Trump for president|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/dennis-rodman-endorses-donald-trump-2016-president-120592.html|accessdate=July 25, 2015|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===North Korea visits===\n{{See also|Kenneth Bae#Dennis Rodman}}\nOn February 26, 2013, Rodman made a trip to North Korea with [[Vice (magazine)|Vice Media]] correspondent [[Ryan Duffy (correspondent)|Ryan Duffy]] to host basketball exhibitions.<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zinser |first1=Lynn |title=Tensions Rising With North Korea, but Dennis Rodman Is There |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/27/sports/basketball/dennis-rodman-arrives-in-north-korea-for-tour.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |date=February 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/02/26/world/asia/north-korea-globetrotters/index.html?hpt=wo_t3|title=Dennis Rodman to North Korea: 'I come in peace'|first=By Alan|last=Duke|publisher=}}</ref> He met North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]].<ref>{{cite news|journal=ABC News |title=Rodman Worms His Way Into Kim Jong Un Meeting |date=February 28, 2013 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2013/02/rodman-worms-his-way-into-kim-jong-un-meeting/ |last1=Cho |first1=Joohee |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301041619/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2013/02/rodman-worms-his-way-into-kim-jong-un-meeting/ |archivedate=March 1, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=FlorCruz|first=Michelle|title=Dennis Rodman And Kim Jong-Un Chat Courtside At Pyongyang Basketball Game|date=February 28, 2013|newspaper=International Business Times|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/dennis-rodman-kim-jong-un-chat-courtside-pyongyang-basketball-game-1107404|accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref> Rodman and his travel party were the first Americans to meet Kim.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Choe |first1=Sang-Hun |last2=Sanger |first2=David E. |title=Way to Reach Kim Jong-un? Follow the Ball |date=March 1, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/02/world/asia/way-to-reach-kim-jong-un-follow-the-ball.html?pagewanted=2&_r=0&pagewanted=all |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130411141308/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/02/world/asia/way-to-reach-kim-jong-un-follow-the-ball.html?pagewanted=2&_r=1&pagewanted=all& |archivedate=April 11, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> He later said that Kim was \"a friend for life\"<ref name=\"Vice 2013\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/vice-tracks-rodman-strange-days-north-korea-article-1.1357860 | title='Vice' season finale on HBO gives fresh look at Dennis Rodman's meeting with North Korea's Kim Jong-un | publisher=NEW YORK DAILY NEWS | date=May 29, 2013 | accessdate=July 16, 2013 | author=Silverman, Justin Rocket}}</ref> and suggested that President [[Barack Obama]] \"pick up the phone and call\" Kim, since the two leaders were basketball fans.<ref>{{cite news|last=Blake |first=Aaron |title=Dennis Rodman: Kim Jong Eun is 'my friend' |date=March 3, 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/03/03/dennis-rodman-kim-jong-un-is-my-friend/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304204424/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/03/03/dennis-rodman-kim-jong-un-is-my-friend/ |archivedate=March 4, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 7, after reading an article in ''[[The Seattle Times]]'',<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dennisrodman|author=Dennis Rodman|number=331833882578145282|date=May 7, 2013|title=In direct response to your article headline, \"Ok.\" Read your story @uscthanhtan, and I decided to help.}}</ref> Rodman sent out a tweet asking Kim to release American prisoner [[Kenneth Bae]], who had been sentenced to 15 years of hard labor in North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2013/05/07/dennis_rodman_calls_on_kim_jong_un_to_release_american_detainee|title=Dennis Rodman calls on Kim Jong Un to do him 'a solid' and release American detainee|publisher=Foreign Policy|author=Uri Friedman|date=May 7, 2013|accessdate=May 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=dennisrodman|author=Dennis Rodman|number=331826019747127297|date=May 7, 2013|title=I'm calling on the Supreme Leader of North Korea or as I call him \"Kim\", to do me a solid and cut Kenneth Bae loose.}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated34\" /> Kim released Bae the following year.\n\nIn July 2013, Rodman told ''Sports Illustrated'': \"My mission is to break the ice between hostile countries. Why it's been left to me to smooth things over, I don't know. Dennis Rodman, of all people. Keeping us safe is really not my job; it's the black guy's [Obama's] job. But I'll tell you this: If I don't finish in the top three for the next Nobel Peace Prize, something's seriously wrong.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated34\" /> On September 3, 2013, Rodman flew to Pyongyang for another meeting with Kim Jong-un.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rodman returns to Pyongyang but says won't bring back jailed American|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/03/us-korea-north-rodman-idUSBRE98200X20130903|agency=Reuters|accessdate=September 3, 2013}}</ref> He said that Kim has a daughter named [[Kim Ju-ae]], and that he is a \"great dad\".<ref>{{cite web|last=McDevitt|first=Caitlin|title=Rodman: Kim Jong Un is 'a great dad'|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/click/2013/09/rodman-kim-jongun-is-a-great-dad-172118.html?hp=r11|publisher=Politico|accessdate=September 9, 2013}}</ref> He also noted that he planned to train the [[North Korean national basketball team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/dennis-rodman-to-train-north-korean-olympic-basketball-team/ |title=Dennis Rodman To Train North Korea Olympic Basketball Team |publisher=Mediaite |date=September 9, 2013 |accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref> He stated that he is \"trying to open Obama's and everyone's minds\" and encouraged Obama to reach out to Kim Jong-un.<ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea: Reality vs. The World According to Dennis Rodman|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/09/world/north-korea-world-according-to-dennis-rodman/|publisher=CNN.com|author=Josh Levs|accessdate=September 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Rodman announced that he would visit North Korea again. He also said that he has plans to take a number of former NBA players with him for an exhibition basketball tour.<ref>{{cite news|last=Helin|first=Kurt|title=Dennis Rodman still planning exhibition game in North Korea with former NBA players|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/11/22/dennis-rodman-still-planning-exhibition-game-in-north-korea-with-former-nba-players/|newspaper=NBC Sports}}</ref> According to Rory Scott, a spokesman for the exhibitions' sponsoring organization, Rodman planned to visit December 18\u201321 and train the North Korean team in preparation for January games. The games were scheduled for January 8 (Kim Jong-un's birthday) and January 10, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rodman Heading Back to NKorea to Train Basketball Team|url=http://www.newsmaxworld.com/Asia/nkorea-rodman-basketball-team/2013/12/04/id/539920|publisher=AFP|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> Included on the U.S. exhibition team were [[Kenny Anderson (basketball)|Kenny Anderson]], [[Cliff Robinson (basketball, born 1966)|Cliff Robinson]], [[Vin Baker]], [[Craig Hodges]], [[Doug Christie (basketball)|Doug Christie]], [[Sleepy Floyd]], [[Charles D. Smith]], and four streetballers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefloridanewsjournal.com/2014/01/06/dennis-rodman-announces-basketball-diplomacy-upcoming-games-north-korea |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 29, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106142922/http://www.thefloridanewsjournal.com/2014/01/06/dennis-rodman-announces-basketball-diplomacy-upcoming-games-north-korea |archivedate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> Rodman departed from Beijing on January 6. Among his entourage was Irish media personality [[Matt Cooper (Irish journalist)|Matt Cooper]], who had interviewed Rodman a number of times on the radio.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dennis Rodman departs for North Korea basketball exhibition |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0106/496115-rodman-north-korea/ |website=rte.ie |accessdate=January 6, 2014 |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Connell |first1=Hugh |title=Today FM's Matt Cooper is in North Korea with Dennis Rodman |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/today-fm-matt-cooper-denis-rodman-north-korea-1250869-Jan2014/ |website=TheJournal.ie |accessdate=January 6, 2014 |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nRodman made comments on January 7, 2014 during a CNN interview implying that Kenneth Bae was at fault for his imprisonment. The remarks were widely reported in other media outlets and provoked a storm of criticism. Two days later, Rodman apologized for his comments, saying that he had been drinking and under pressure. He added that he \"should know better than to make political statements\". Some members of Congress, the NBA, and human rights groups suggested that Rodman had become a public relations stunt for the North Korean government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dennis Rodman: 'I had been drinking' |date=January 9, 2014 |work=ESPN.com |agency=Associated Press |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/10267308/dennis-rodman-apologizes-comments-jailed-american |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109235254/http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/10267308/dennis-rodman-apologizes-comments-jailed-american |archivedate=January 9, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 2, 2016, Kenneth Bae credited Rodman with his early release. He said that Rodman's rant raised awareness of his case and that he wanted to thank him for his expedited release.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dennis Rodman's ranting saved me from North Korean gulag|url=https://nypost.com/2016/05/02/dennis-rodmans-ranting-saved-me-from-north-korean-gulag/|publisher=New York Post|author=David K. Li|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Department of the Treasury is reportedly investigating whether Rodman broke the law by bringing Kim Jong-un thousands of dollars in luxury gifts on his 2014 trip to North Korea.<ref name=\"violations\">{{cite news | url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/01/25/feds-reportedly-investigating-rodman-for-violating-sanctions-against-n-korea/ | title=Feds reportedly investigating Rodman for violating sanctions against N. Korea | date=January 25, 2014 | agency=foxnews.com | accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2017, Rodman returned to North Korea on what was initially described as a sports-related visit to the country. \"My purpose is to go over there and try to see if I can keep bringing sports to North Korea,\" he said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/13/politics/dennis-rodman-north-korea/index.html|title=Dennis Rodman hopes to do 'something pretty positive' in North Korea|author=Matt Rivers, Will Ripley and Joshua Berlinger|website=CNN|access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> He added that he hoped to accomplish \"something that's pretty positive\" during the visit. He met with national Olympic athletes and basketball players, viewed a men's basketball practice, and visited a state-run orphanage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/sports-life/dennis-rodman-gives-north-korean-minister-a-copy-of-donald-trumps-the-art-of-the-deal/news-story/c708b7d1df91bbbe9da4af18b5ab5b6d|title=Rodman gives Trump's book to Kim|work=NewsComAu|access-date=June 16, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/rodman-north-korean-official-trumps-art-deal-48049098|title=Rodman gives Kim the gift of Trump: 'The Art of the Deal'|last=News|first=ABC|work=ABC News|access-date=June 16, 2017|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616001236/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/rodman-north-korean-official-trumps-art-deal-48049098|archivedate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> He was not able to meet with Kim Jong Un, but met instead with the nation's Minister of Sports and gave him several gifts for Kim Jong Un, including two signed basketball jerseys, two soap sets, and a copy of Donald Trump's 1987 book ''[[Trump: The Art of the Deal|The Art of the Deal]]''.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/06/15/dennis-rodman-just-gave-kim-jong-un-the-art-of-the-deal-and-it-may-be-a-genius-move/|title=Dennis Rodman just gave Kim Jong Un 'The Art of the Deal.' And it may be a genius move.|website=Washington Post|access-date=June 16, 2017}}</ref> Other gifts believed to be intended for the leader's daughter included a ''[[Where's Wally?|Where's Waldo?]]'' book and a jigsaw puzzle of a mermaid.\n\nRodman posted a video on Twitter that was recorded before he left for the visit in which he and his agent describe the mission of the trip. \"He's going to try to bring peace between both nations,\" said Rodman's agent Chris Volo, referring to the strained relations between North Korea and the United States. Rodman added, \"That's the main reason why we're going. We're trying to bring everything together. If not, at least we tried.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The visit was sponsored by the cryptocurrency company [[PotCoin]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Montrealers funding Dennis Rodman's trip to North Korea|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/dennis-rodman-potcoin-1.4161371|accessdate=May 13, 2018|work=CBC News Montreal|agency=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|publisher=CBC/Radio-Canada|date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRodman's \"hoops diplomacy\" inspired the [[20th Century Fox]] comedy ''Diplomats''. [[Tim Story]] and [[Peter Chernin]] are set to produce the film, while Jonathan Abrams is reportedly writing the script.<ref name=\"Siegel-North Korea\">{{cite news|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|title=Dennis Rodman North Korea Mission to Become Fox Movie (Exclusive)|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/ride-along-director-tim-story-682690|accessdate=February 24, 2014|newspaper=Hollywood Reporter|date=February 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Carson-North Korea\">{{cite news|last=Carson|first=Dan|title=Report: Movie Based on Dennis Rodman's North Korea Trips in Development|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1971542-report-movie-based-on-dennis-rodmans-north-korea-trips-in-development|accessdate=February 24, 2014|newspaper=Bleacher Report|date=February 24, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Armitage-North Korea\">{{cite news|last=Armitage|first=Hugh|title=Kim Jong-un, Dennis Rodman film planned by Ride Along director Tim Story |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a553298/kim-jong-un-dennis-rodman-film-planned-by-ride-along-director-tim-story.html|accessdate=February 24, 2014|newspaper=Digital Spy|date=February 24, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Feldman-North Korea\">{{cite news|last=Feldman|first=Brian|title=Dennis Rodman's Basketball Diplomacy Is Getting Turned into a Movie|url=http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/02/dennis-rodmans-basketball-diplomacy-getting-turned-movie/358429/|accessdate=February 24, 2014|newspaper=The Wire|date=February 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nRodman visited North Korea again in June 2018. \"I'm just happy to be a part of\" the [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States summit]], he said, \"because I think I deserve it.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hains |first1=Tim |title=Dennis Rodman Arrives In Singapore Ahead of Trump-Kim Summit: \"The Door Is Open\" |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2018/06/11/dennis_rodman_arrives_in_singapore_ahead_of_trump-kim_summit.html |website=RealClearPolitics |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Presidential involvement suggested====\n''[[The Washington Post]]'' raised the question of whether President Donald Trump sent Rodman on his 2017 visit to negotiate the release of several American prisoners of North Korea or to open a back channel for diplomatic communications.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/dennis-rodman-is-on-his-way-to-north-korea-was-he-sent-by-trump/2017/06/12/5c9c19cc-4fd9-11e7-a973-3dae94ed3eb7_story.html|title=Dennis Rodman is back in North Korea. Was he sent by Trump?|website=Washington Post|access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> The U.S. State Department, White House officials, and Rodman all denied any official government involvement in the visit. Rodman, who publicly endorsed Trump during the 2016 presidential campaign, is a self-described longtime friend of the president and, as the article put it, \"Trump and Kim's only mutual acquaintance.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> ''The Washington Post'' article stated, \"Multiple people involved in unofficial talks with North Korea say that the Trump administration has been making overtures toward the Kim regime, including trying to set up a secret back channel to the North Korean leader using 'an associate of Trump's' rather than the usual lineup of North Korea experts and former officials who talk to Pyongyang's representatives.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWhen asked if he had spoken with Trump about the visit, Rodman replied, \"Well, I'm pretty sure he's pretty much happy with the fact that I'm over here trying to accomplish something that we both need.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/world/asia/dennis-rodman-north-korea.html|title=Dennis Rodman, Frequent Visitor to North Korea, Is Back|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=June 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 13, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Rodman publicly presented a copy of Trump's book, \"The Art of the Deal\" to North Korean officials, as a personal gift for Kim Jong Un. In a Twitter video posted by Rodman, his agent Chris Volo said, \"He's the only person on the planet that has the uniqueness, the unbelievable privilege of being friends with President Trump and Marshal Kim Jong Un.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Rodman went on to say in the video that he wanted to bring peace and \"open doors between both countries.\"\n\n[[Otto Warmbier]], an American student held captive in North Korea for 17 months, was released to U.S. officials the same day as Rodman's visit to North Korea. Despite the timeline of the two events, the U.S. State Department, The White House, and Rodman all flatly denied any diplomatic connection or coordination between Rodman's visit and the U.S. government. The U.S. State Department said the release of Warmbier was negotiated and secured by high level U.S. diplomats including [[Joseph Y. Yun|Joseph Yun]], the State Department's special envoy on North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-northkorea-detainee-idUSKBN1941UX|title=High-level U.S. visit leads North Korea to free student in coma|date=June 14, 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=June 16, 2017}}</ref> Warmbier, who was in a nonresponsive coma throughout much of his imprisonment in North Korea, died days after being returned to his family in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/06/19/otto-warmbier-dies-days-after-release-from-north-korean-detainment/|title=Otto Warmbier dies days after release from North Korean detention|website=Washington Post|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn an emotional interview with [[Michael Strahan]] of \"[[Good Morning America]]\", Rodman expressed sorrow for the death of Warmbier and said, \"I was just so happy to see the kid released. Later that day, that's when we found out he was ill. No one knew that.\" He added that he wished to give \"all the prayer and love\" to the Warmbier family and had contacted them and hoped to meet with them personally.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/dennis-rodman-people-good-side-north-korea/story?id=48224976|title=Dennis Rodman speaks out about his visit to North Korea|date=June 23, 2017|website=ABC News|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRodman's agent, Chris Volo, told ABC News that before they left for the 2017 trip, he had asked North Korean officials to release Warmbier as a symbol of good faith for any future sports-relations visits. \"I asked on behalf of Dennis for his release three times,\" Volo said.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn December 2017, [[Columbia University]] professor of [[neurobiology]] [[Joseph Terwilliger]], who has accompanied Rodman to North Korea, argued that \"While I don't suspect that very many Americans would have chosen him to be an emissary or international goodwill ambassador, Dennis has had a long friendship with Mr. Trump and has also developed a very cordial friendship with Mr. Kim. In this tense climate, as we stand at a perilous crossing, Mr. Rodman's unique position as a friend to the leaders of both U.S. and North Korea could provide a much-needed bridge to help resolve the current nuclear standoff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/dec/6/blocking-nuclear-war-would-be-a-win-for-both-the-u/|title=Blocking nuclear war would be a win for both the U.S., North Korea|first=The Washington Times|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book |title=Rebound: The Dennis Rodman Story |first=Dennis |last=Rodman |year=1994 |isbn=0-517-59294-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/rebounddennisrod00rodm}}\n* {{cite book|title= Bad as I Wanna Be |first=Dennis |last=Rodman | year=1996|isbn=0-440-22266-4|title-link=Bad as I Wanna Be}}\n* {{cite book |title=Walk on the Wild Side |first=Dennis |last=Rodman |year=1997 |isbn=0-385-31897-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/walkonwildside00rodm}}\n* {{cite book|title=I Should Be Dead by Now |first=Dennis |last=Rodman | year=2005|isbn=1-59670-016-5}}\n* {{cite book|title=Dennis the Wild Bull |first=Dennis |last=Rodman | year=2013|isbn=978-0-61575-249-5|title-link=Dennis the Wild Bull}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Biography}}\n* [[List of career achievements by Dennis Rodman]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association career rebounding leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association career playoff rebounding leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association annual rebounding leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association single-game rebounding leaders]]\n\n==Notes==\n* {{note label|Note1|a|a}} Rodman's height has been listed at {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}, {{convert|6|ft|7|in|m|abbr=on}}, or {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on}}. NBA.com itself has been inconsistent.<ref name=\"nba_historical\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Dennis Rodman |url=https://stats.nba.com/player/23/career/ |website=stats.nba.com |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dennis Rodman |url=http://www.nba.com/history/players/rodman_stats.html |website=NBA.com |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303222750/http://www.nba.com/history/players/rodman_stats.html |archivedate=March 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dennis Rodman Stats, News, Bio |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/player/_/id/726/dennis-rodman |website=ESPN |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{basketballstats|nba=23|bbr=r/rodmade01}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|0005379}}\n* [http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/d/dennis-rodman.html Online World of Wrestling profile]\n* [http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=6407&gimmick=Dennis+Rodman CageMatch profile]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Dennis Rodman \u2013 Basketball career\n|list1=\n{{1986 NBA Draft}}\n{{Detroit Pistons}}\n{{Detroit Pistons 1988\u201389 NBA champions}}\n{{Detroit Pistons 1989\u201390 NBA champions}}\n{{Chicago Bulls 1995\u201396 NBA champions}}\n{{Chicago Bulls 1996\u201397 NBA champions}}\n{{Chicago Bulls 1997\u201398 NBA champions}}\n{{NBA Defensive Players of the Year}}\n{{IBM Award}}\n{{NBA rebounding leaders}}\n{{Basketball Hall of Fame}}\n{{2011 Basketball HOF}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Dennis 