{"title_page": "Austin Barnes", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Austin Barnes\n|image       = Austin Barnes 2017.jpg\n|image_size  = 220px\n|caption     = Barnes with the [[2018 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers in 2018]]\n|team        = Los Angeles Dodgers\n|number      = 15\n|position    = [[Catcher]] / [[Second baseman]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1989|12|28}}\n|birth_place = [[Riverside, California]]\n|bats        = Right\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = May 24\n|debutyear   = 2015\n|debutteam   = Los Angeles Dodgers\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value  = .229\n|stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n|stat2value  = 17\n|stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value  = 80\n|teams=\n*[[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2015}}\u2013present)\n|highlights  =\n}}\n'''Austin Scott Barnes''' (born December 28, 1989) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]] for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He made his MLB debut in 2015. In addition to catching, Barnes has also played as an [[infielder]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Amateur career===\nBarnes was born in [[Riverside, California]]<ref name=cube>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?P=austin-barnes |title=Austin Barnes Baseball Statistics |work=Baseball Cube |accessdate=January 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316040514/http://thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?P=austin-barnes |archivedate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> and attended [[Riverside Polytechnic High School]]. He played [[college baseball]] at [[Arizona State University]] for the [[Arizona State Sun Devils baseball|Arizona State Sun Devils]] from 2009 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/2011/03/24/20110324asu-baseball-arizona-preview-tempe.html|title=ASU's Austin Barnes is locked in behind and at the plate|work=The Arizona Republic|first=Jeff|last=Metcalfe|date=March 24, 2011|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> Before his sophomore season in 2010 he moved from infield to catcher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/2010/04/29/20100429arizona-state-sun-devils-baseball-austin-barnes.html|title=Arizona State Sun Devils baseball's Austin Barnes making transition from infield to catcher|work=Arizona Republic|first=Jeff|last=Metcalfe|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> During his career he played in 109 games and hit .308/.379/.429 with two [[home runs]].<ref name=cube/> For the [[Oklahoma City Dodgers]], he played every position except pitcher.\n\n===Miami Marlins===\nBarnes was selected by the [[Florida Marlins]] in the eighth round of the [[2011 Major League Baseball draft]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/index.cgi?team_ID=FLA&year_ID=2011&draft_type=junreg&query_type=franch_year|title=2011 Florida Marlins picks in the June Draft|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> and made his professional debut that season for the [[Jamestown Jammers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnewsdaily.com/sports/jammers/story/Barnes-Finds-Fit-Behind-The-Plate-2011-07-23 |title=Barnes Finds Fit Behind The Plate |work=StarNewsDaily |first=Scott |last=Eddy |date=July 23, 2011 |accessdate=May 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016180411/http://www.starnewsdaily.com/sports/jammers/story/Barnes-Finds-Fit-Behind-The-Plate-2011-07-23 |archivedate=October 16, 2014 }}</ref> From 2012 to 2014 he played for the [[Greensboro Grasshoppers]], [[Jupiter Hammerheads]] and [[Jacksonville Suns]].<ref name=minors>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=barnes000aus|title=Austin Barnes minor league statistics & history|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> He split time between catcher and second base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/-716494--.html|title=MINOR LEAGUE BASEBALL: Barnes succeeding at second, catcher|work=The Press Enterprise|first=David|last=Lassen|date=July 5, 2012|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers===\n[[File:Austin Barnes, 2015 Triple-A All-Star Game.jpg|left|thumb|Barnes with the [[Oklahoma City Dodgers]] at the {{Baseball year|2015}} [[Triple-A All-Star Game]]]]\nOn December 10, 2014, Barnes was traded to the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], along with [[Chris Hatcher (pitcher)|Chris Hatcher]], [[Andrew Heaney]], and [[Enrique Hern\u00e1ndez (baseball)|Enrique Hern\u00e1ndez]], in exchange for [[Dan Haren]], [[Dee Gordon]], [[Miguel Rojas (baseball)|Miguel Rojas]] and cash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/103746900/dodgers-adding-howie-kendrick-jimmy-rollins-in-trades|title=Dodgers adding Kendrick, Rollins in trades|last=Gurnick|first=Ken|work=MLB.com|date=December 11, 2014|accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref> He was assigned to the AAA [[Oklahoma City Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/dodgers/2015/04/07/revealed-opening-day-roster-for-triple-a-oklahoma-city/|title=Revealed: Opening Day roster for Triple-A Oklahoma City.|work=LA Daily News|first=J.P.|last=Hoornstra|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> On May 23, 2015, he was called up to the Major Leagues for the first time when [[Yasmani Grandal]] went on the 7-Day DL with a concussion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.dodgers.mlb.com/news/article/126199808/grandal-placed-on-7-day-concussion-list|title=Grandal placed on 7-day concussion list|work=mlb.com|first=Ken|last=Gurnick|date=May 23, 2015|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\nHe made his MLB debut as the starting catcher for the Dodgers on May 24, 2015,originally wearing number 65.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truebluela.com/2015/5/24/8652819/austin-barnes-major-league-debut-dodgers-padres-preview|title=Dodgers notes: Austin Barnes debuts, Juan Uribe's diminished role, Yasmani Grandal on the mend|work=SB Nation|date=May 24, 2015|accessdate=May 24, 2015|first=Eric|last=Stephen}}</ref> and had one hit in three at-bats in his debut, with his first MLB hit being a single to center field off of [[Dale Thayer]] of the [[San Diego Padres]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2015_05_24_sdnmlb_lanmlb_1#game=2015_05_24_sdnmlb_lanmlb_1,game_tab=play-by-play,game_state=Wrapup|title=Padres 11, Dodgers 3 play-by-play|work=mlb.com|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> He returned to Oklahoma City after his short time on the Dodgers roster and was named as a starter on the [[Pacific Coast League]] team for the mid-season Triple-A All-Star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20150701&content_id=134023050&fext=.jsp&vkey=pr_t238&sid=t238|title=Four OKC Dodgers Named to Triple-A All-Star Game|work=milb.com|date=July 1, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> He was also named to the post-season PCL all-star team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20150831&content_id=146452978&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t238&sid=t238|title=OKC DODGERS CATCHER BARNES NAMED TO ALL-PCL TEAM|author=Oklahoma City Dodgers|work=milb.com|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> and [[Baseball America]]'s Triple-A All-Star team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/minors/2015-classification-star-teams/|title=2015 Minor League Classification All-Star Teams|work=Baseball America|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> He rejoined the Dodgers in September<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/dodgers-680311-guys-seager.html|title=Dodgers' September call-ups begin arriving, including Austin Barnes for injured Kik\u00e9 Hernandez|first=Bill|last=Plunkett|work=Orange County Register|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> He played in 20 games for the Dodgers with six hits in 29 at-bats (.207).<ref name=br>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/barneau01.shtml|title=Austin Barnes Statistics & History|work=Baseball Reference}}</ref> In 81 games for the Oklahoma City team, he hit .315 with nine homers and 42 RBI.<ref name=minors/>\n[[File:Austin Barnes on July 24, 2015.jpg|thumb|Barnes with the [[2015 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers in 2015]]]]\n\nBarnes appeared in 21 games for the Dodgers in 2016, hitting .156<ref name=br/> and 85 games for Oklahoma City, hitting .295. He changed his number from 65 to 28.<ref name=minors/> He also appeared in two games in the [[2016 National League Division Series]] against the [[Washington Nationals]], with one pinch hit appearance and one pinch run appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2016_NLDS2.shtml|title=2016 NL Division Series (3-2): Los Angeles Dodgers (91-71) over Washington Nationals (95-67)|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBarnes made the Opening Day roster as the backup catcher in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2017/4/2/15145108/dodgers-opening-day-roster-disabled-list|title=Dodgers announce opening day roster, place 5 on disabled list|work=SB Nation|first=Eric|last=Stephen|date=April 2, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref>  On June 30, 2017, Barnes recorded his first multi-homer game of his career (his first career grand slam and a three run home run) and recorded a career high seven RBIs against the [[San Diego Padres]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2017/6/30/15907308/austin-barnes-home-runs-alex-wood-strikeouts-dodgers-padres-blowout-again|title=Austin Barnes powers Dodgers over Padres|work=SB Nation|first=Eric|last=Stephen|date=June 30, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> He gradually saw more playing time, moving into a platoon role with Grandal for most of the season before taking over as the starter in the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-dodgers-cubs-live-game-3-dave-roberts-talks-about-austin-barnes-1508286953-htmlstory.html|title=Dave Roberts talks about Austin Barnes starting over Yasmani Grandal|first=Andy|last=McCullough|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 17, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> During the regular season, he had a .289 batting average with eight home runs and 38 RBI in 102 games.<ref name=br/> In the [[2017 NLDS]] he had four hits in eight at-bats with a home run and a double in the Dodgers' three-game sweep of the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]].<ref name=br/> In the [[2017 NLCS]] against the [[Chicago Cubs]], he had two hits in 15 at-bats and in the [[2017 World Series]] against the [[Houston Astros]], he had four hits in 23 at-bats.<ref name=br/> \n\nIn 2018, Barnes started [[Spring Training]] battling elbow discomfort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/dodgers/la-sp-dodgers-austin-barnes-elbow-20180222-story.html|title=Dodgers Catcher Austin Barnes dealing with elbow discomfort|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Andy|last=McCullough|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> He ended up being the backup to [[Yasmani Grandal]], taking over the catching role more in the [[Postseason]] when Grandal allowed two passed balls and made two errors in game 1 of the NLCS and another passed ball in game 3, resulting in Dodgers fans booing him and begging for Barnes to catch.<ref name=br/> Barnes hit .205/.329/.290 in 100 games with 4 homeruns, 41 hits, and 14 RBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2018/12/24/18155058/2018-dodgers-review-austin-barnes-starting-catcher-in-waiting|title=2018 Dodgers Review:Austin Barnes|work=SB Nation|first=Craig|last=Minami|date=December 24, 2018|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> An elite framer, he excelled defensively.<ref name=br/> He ranked third in the MLB for framing and defensive statistics, had a .993 fielding percentage, and allowed only one passed ball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statcorner.com/CatcherReport.php|title=StatCorner Catcher Report|work=StatCorner|first=Matthew|last=Carruth|date=2018|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018 NLCS]] against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]], Barnes had two hits in 18 at-bats.<ref name=br/> In the [[2018 World Series]] against the [[Boston Red Sox]], he was hitless in eleven at-bats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/barneau01.shtml|title=Austin Barnes|work=Baseball Reference}}</ref> His best game in 2018 came on September 4 against the [[New York Mets]], where he crushed a two-run homerun, putting the Dodgers on the board for the first time in the game and ultimately leading to a 11-4 victory over the Mets.<ref name=br/>\n\nIn [[2019 Major League Baseball season|2019]], Barnes was named the Opening Day starting catcher after Grandal signed with the [[Milwaukee Brewers]]. However, he got off to a slow start and on July 26 he was sent down to Oklahoma City to make room for rookie catcher [[Will Smith (catcher)|Will Smith]] to take over the everyday catching duties. Barnes was batting .196 prior to being sent down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/dodgers/story/2019-07-26/will-smith-dodgers-catcher-austin-barnes-david-freese|title=Rookie Will Smith to be Dodgers\u2019 \u2018primary\u2019 catcher, Dave Roberts says|work=LA Times|first=Jorge|last=Castillo|date=July 26, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref> He appeared in only 75 games in the majors in 2019, hitting .203,<ref name=br/> while he hit .264 in 23 games in the minor leagues.<ref name=minors/> Barnes signed a one-year, $1.1 million, contract with the Dodgers after the season, avoiding arbitration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/dodgers/news/dodgers-avoid-arbitration-with-austin-barnes|title=Dodgers avoid arb with Barnes, non-tender Yimi|first=Ken|last=Gurnick|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=December 3, 2019|work=mlb.com}}</ref>\n\n== Nickname ==\nAustin Barnes wore his rookie-year nickname \"SAM\" on his jersey during the 2018 MLB [[Players Weekend]]. This nickname originated when Barnes was sent on a taco run during [[spring training]]. Upon returning to the clubhouse, teammate [[A. J. Ellis]] joked that [[Chase Utley]] didn't know Barnes' name. Utley replied that he knows that it is Sam, and the name stuck.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/dodgers-nicknames-for-2018-players-weekend-c289583540|title=Dodgers' nicknames for 2018 Players' Weekend|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/dodgers-players-weekend-names-breakdown-c250393424|title=Dodgers' Players Weekend names breakdown|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-mlb-players-nicknames-20170809-story.html|title=MLB players get to wear nicknames on their jerseys for one weekend: So which Dodger is \u2018Dizzy\u2019? Or \u2018Sam\u2019?|last=Schilken|first=Chuck|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2018/8/10/17675360/ranking-the-dodgers-2018-players-weekend-nicknames|title=Ranking Players' Weekend Nicknames|last=fbihop|date=2018-08-10|website=True Blue LA|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarnes is the nephew of former MLB infielder [[Mike Gallego]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/2017/07/04/austin-barnes-and-the-tools-of-persistence/|title=Austin Barnes and the tools of persistence|work=Orange County Register|first=Mark|last=Whicker|date=July 4, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> His younger brother, Griffin, played catcher for [[Grand Canyon University]] and recently signed with the [[Los Angeles Angels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gculopes.com/news/2018/6/9/baseball-barnes-signs-with-angels.aspx?path=baseball|title=Barnes signs with the Angels|work=Grand Canyon University|first=Josh|last=Hauser|date=June 11, 2018|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> His favorite actor is [[Will Ferrell]] and he enjoys playing [[golf]] in his free time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thesundevils.com/news/2013/4/17/208245639.aspx|title=Player Profile: Austin Barnes - Arizona State University Official Athletic Site|work=Arizona State University|date=April 17, 2013|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Austin Barnes}}\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n{{Baseballstats |mlb=605131 |espn=32856 |br=b/barneau01 |fangraphs=12158|brm=barnes000aus}}\n*[http://www.thesundevils.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30300&ATCLID=208245639 Arizona State Sun Devils bio]\n\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Austin}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Riverside, California]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Arizona State Sun Devils baseball players]]\n[[Category:Jamestown Jammers players]]\n[[Category:Greensboro Grasshoppers players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Suns players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Rancho Cucamonga Quakes players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Austin Barnes\n|image       = Austin Barnes 2017.jpg\n|image_size  = 220px\n|caption     = Barnes with the [[2018 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers in 2018]]\n|team        = Los Angeles Dodgers\n|number      = 15\n|position    = [[Catcher]] / [[Second baseman]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1989|12|28}}\n|birth_place = [[Riverside, California]]\n|bats        = Right\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = May 24\n|debutyear   = 2015\n|debutteam   = Los Angeles Dodgers\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value  = .229\n|stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n|stat2value  = 17\n|stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value  = 80\n|teams=\n*[[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2015}}\u2013present)\n|highlights  =\n}}\n'''Austin Scott Barnes''' (born December 28, 1989) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]] for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He made his MLB debut in 2015. In addition to catching, Barnes has also played as an [[infielder]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Amateur career===\nBarnes was born in [[Riverside, California]]<ref name=cube>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?P=austin-barnes |title=Austin Barnes Baseball Statistics |work=Baseball Cube |accessdate=January 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316040514/http://thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?P=austin-barnes |archivedate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> and attended [[Riverside Polytechnic High School]]. He played [[college baseball]] at [[Arizona State University]] for the [[Arizona State Sun Devils baseball|Arizona State Sun Devils]] from 2009 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/2011/03/24/20110324asu-baseball-arizona-preview-tempe.html|title=ASU's Austin Barnes is locked in behind and at the plate|work=The Arizona Republic|first=Jeff|last=Metcalfe|date=March 24, 2011|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> Before his sophomore season in 2010 he moved from infield to catcher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/2010/04/29/20100429arizona-state-sun-devils-baseball-austin-barnes.html|title=Arizona State Sun Devils baseball's Austin Barnes making transition from infield to catcher|work=Arizona Republic|first=Jeff|last=Metcalfe|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> During his career he played in 109 games and hit .308/.379/.429 with two [[home runs]].<ref name=cube/> For the [[Oklahoma City Dodgers]], he played every position except pitcher.\n\n===Miami Marlins===\nBarnes was selected by the [[Florida Marlins]] in the eighth round of the [[2011 Major League Baseball draft]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/index.cgi?team_ID=FLA&year_ID=2011&draft_type=junreg&query_type=franch_year|title=2011 Florida Marlins picks in the June Draft|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> and made his professional debut that season for the [[Jamestown Jammers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnewsdaily.com/sports/jammers/story/Barnes-Finds-Fit-Behind-The-Plate-2011-07-23 |title=Barnes Finds Fit Behind The Plate |work=StarNewsDaily |first=Scott |last=Eddy |date=July 23, 2011 |accessdate=May 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016180411/http://www.starnewsdaily.com/sports/jammers/story/Barnes-Finds-Fit-Behind-The-Plate-2011-07-23 |archivedate=October 16, 2014 }}</ref> From 2012 to 2014 he played for the [[Greensboro Grasshoppers]], [[Jupiter Hammerheads]] and [[Jacksonville Suns]].<ref name=minors>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=barnes000aus|title=Austin Barnes minor league statistics & history|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> He split time between catcher and second base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/-716494--.html|title=MINOR LEAGUE BASEBALL: Barnes succeeding at second, catcher|work=The Press Enterprise|first=David|last=Lassen|date=July 5, 2012|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers===\n[[File:Austin Barnes, 2015 Triple-A All-Star Game.jpg|left|thumb|Barnes with the [[Oklahoma City Dodgers]] at the {{Baseball year|2015}} [[Triple-A All-Star Game]]]]\nOn December 10, 2014, Barnes was traded to the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], along with [[Chris Hatcher (pitcher)|Chris Hatcher]], [[Andrew Heaney]], and [[Enrique Hern\u00e1ndez (baseball)|Enrique Hern\u00e1ndez]], in exchange for [[Dan Haren]], [[Dee Gordon]], [[Miguel Rojas (baseball)|Miguel Rojas]] and cash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/103746900/dodgers-adding-howie-kendrick-jimmy-rollins-in-trades|title=Dodgers adding Kendrick, Rollins in trades|last=Gurnick|first=Ken|work=MLB.com|date=December 11, 2014|accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref> He was assigned to the AAA [[Oklahoma City Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/dodgers/2015/04/07/revealed-opening-day-roster-for-triple-a-oklahoma-city/|title=Revealed: Opening Day roster for Triple-A Oklahoma City.|work=LA Daily News|first=J.P.|last=Hoornstra|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> On May 23, 2015, he was called up to the Major Leagues for the first time when [[Yasmani Grandal]] went on the 7-Day DL with a concussion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.dodgers.mlb.com/news/article/126199808/grandal-placed-on-7-day-concussion-list|title=Grandal placed on 7-day concussion list|work=mlb.com|first=Ken|last=Gurnick|date=May 23, 2015|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\nHe made his MLB debut as the starting catcher for the Dodgers on May 24, 2015,originally wearing number 65.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truebluela.com/2015/5/24/8652819/austin-barnes-major-league-debut-dodgers-padres-preview|title=Dodgers notes: Austin Barnes debuts, Juan Uribe's diminished role, Yasmani Grandal on the mend|work=SB Nation|date=May 24, 2015|accessdate=May 24, 2015|first=Eric|last=Stephen}}</ref> and had one hit in three at-bats in his debut, with his first MLB hit being a single to center field off of [[Dale Thayer]] of the [[San Diego Padres]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2015_05_24_sdnmlb_lanmlb_1#game=2015_05_24_sdnmlb_lanmlb_1,game_tab=play-by-play,game_state=Wrapup|title=Padres 11, Dodgers 3 play-by-play|work=mlb.com|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> He returned to Oklahoma City after his short time on the Dodgers roster and was named as a starter on the [[Pacific Coast League]] team for the mid-season Triple-A All-Star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20150701&content_id=134023050&fext=.jsp&vkey=pr_t238&sid=t238|title=Four OKC Dodgers Named to Triple-A All-Star Game|work=milb.com|date=July 1, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> He was also named to the post-season PCL all-star team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20150831&content_id=146452978&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t238&sid=t238|title=OKC DODGERS CATCHER BARNES NAMED TO ALL-PCL TEAM|author=Oklahoma City Dodgers|work=milb.com|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> and [[Baseball America]]'s Triple-A All-Star team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/minors/2015-classification-star-teams/|title=2015 Minor League Classification All-Star Teams|work=Baseball America|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> He rejoined the Dodgers in September<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/dodgers-680311-guys-seager.html|title=Dodgers' September call-ups begin arriving, including Austin Barnes for injured Kik\u00e9 Hernandez|first=Bill|last=Plunkett|work=Orange County Register|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> He played in 20 games for the Dodgers with six hits in 29 at-bats (.207).<ref name=br>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/barneau01.shtml|title=Austin Barnes Statistics & History|work=Baseball Reference}}</ref> In 81 games for the Oklahoma City team, he hit .315 with nine homers and 42 RBI.<ref name=minors/>\n[[File:Austin Barnes on July 24, 2015.jpg|thumb|Barnes with the [[2015 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers in 2015]]]]\n\nBarnes appeared in 21 games for the Dodgers in 2016, hitting .156<ref name=br/> and 85 games for Oklahoma City, hitting .295. He changed his number from 65 to 28.<ref name=minors/> He also appeared in two games in the [[2016 National League Division Series]] against the [[Washington Nationals]], with one pinch hit appearance and one pinch run appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2016_NLDS2.shtml|title=2016 NL Division Series (3-2): Los Angeles Dodgers (91-71) over Washington Nationals (95-67)|work=Baseball Reference|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBarnes made the Opening Day roster as the backup catcher in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2017/4/2/15145108/dodgers-opening-day-roster-disabled-list|title=Dodgers announce opening day roster, place 5 on disabled list|work=SB Nation|first=Eric|last=Stephen|date=April 2, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref>  On June 30, 2017, Barnes recorded his first multi-homer game of his career (his first career grand slam and a three run home run) and recorded a career high seven RBIs against the [[San Diego Padres]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2017/6/30/15907308/austin-barnes-home-runs-alex-wood-strikeouts-dodgers-padres-blowout-again|title=Austin Barnes powers Dodgers over Padres|work=SB Nation|first=Eric|last=Stephen|date=June 30, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> He gradually saw more playing time, moving into a platoon role with Grandal for most of the season before taking over as the starter in the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-dodgers-cubs-live-game-3-dave-roberts-talks-about-austin-barnes-1508286953-htmlstory.html|title=Dave Roberts talks about Austin Barnes starting over Yasmani Grandal|first=Andy|last=McCullough|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 17, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> During the regular season, he had a .289 batting average with eight home runs and 38 RBI in 102 games.<ref name=br/> In the [[2017 NLDS]] he had four hits in eight at-bats with a home run and a double in the Dodgers' three-game sweep of the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]].<ref name=br/> In the [[2017 NLCS]] against the [[Chicago Cubs]], he had two hits in 15 at-bats and in the [[2017 World Series]] against the [[Houston Astros]], he had four hits in 23 at-bats.<ref name=br/> \n\nIn 2018, Barnes started [[Spring Training]] battling elbow discomfort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/dodgers/la-sp-dodgers-austin-barnes-elbow-20180222-story.html|title=Dodgers Catcher Austin Barnes dealing with elbow discomfort|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Andy|last=McCullough|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> He ended up being the backup to [[Yasmani Grandal]], taking over the catching role more in the [[Postseason]] when Grandal allowed two passed balls and made two errors in game 1 of the NLCS and another passed ball in game 3, resulting in Dodgers fans booing him and begging for Barnes to catch.<ref name=br/> Barnes hit .205/.329/.290 in 100 games with 4 homeruns, 41 hits, and 14 RBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2018/12/24/18155058/2018-dodgers-review-austin-barnes-starting-catcher-in-waiting|title=2018 Dodgers Review:Austin Barnes|work=SB Nation|first=Craig|last=Minami|date=December 24, 2018|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> An elite framer, he excelled defensively.<ref name=br/> He ranked third in the MLB for framing and defensive statistics, had a .993 fielding percentage, and allowed only one passed ball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statcorner.com/CatcherReport.php|title=StatCorner Catcher Report|work=StatCorner|first=Matthew|last=Carruth|date=2018|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018 NLCS]] against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]], Barnes had two hits in 18 at-bats.<ref name=br/> In the [[2018 World Series]] against the [[Boston Red Sox]], he was hitless in eleven at-bats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/barneau01.shtml|title=Austin Barnes|work=Baseball Reference}}</ref> His best game in 2018 came on September 4 against the [[New York Mets]], where he crushed a two-run homerun, putting the Dodgers on the board for the first time in the game and ultimately leading to a 11-4 victory over the Mets.<ref name=br/>\n\nIn [[2019 Major League Baseball season|2019]], Barnes was named the Opening Day starting catcher after Grandal signed with the [[Milwaukee Brewers]]. However, he got off to a slow start and on July 26 he was sent down to Oklahoma City to make room for rookie catcher [[Will Smith (catcher)|Will Smith]] to take over the everyday catching duties. Barnes was batting .196 prior to being sent down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/dodgers/story/2019-07-26/will-smith-dodgers-catcher-austin-barnes-david-freese|title=Rookie Will Smith to be Dodgers\u2019 \u2018primary\u2019 catcher, Dave Roberts says|work=LA Times|first=Jorge|last=Castillo|date=July 26, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref> He appeared in only 75 games in the majors in 2019, hitting .203,<ref name=br/> while he hit .264 in 23 games in the minor leagues.<ref name=minors/> Barnes signed a one-year, $1.1 million, contract with the Dodgers after the season, avoiding arbitration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/dodgers/news/dodgers-avoid-arbitration-with-austin-barnes|title=Dodgers avoid arb with Barnes, non-tender Yimi|first=Ken|last=Gurnick|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=December 3, 2019|work=mlb.com}}</ref>\n\n== Nickname ==\nAustin Barnes wore his rookie-year nickname \"SAM\" on his jersey during the 2018 MLB [[Players Weekend]]. This nickname originated when Barnes was sent on a taco run during [[spring training]]. Upon returning to the clubhouse, teammate [[A. J. Ellis]] joked that [[Chase Utley]] didn't know Barnes' name. Utley replied that he knows that it is Sam, and the name stuck.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/dodgers-nicknames-for-2018-players-weekend-c289583540|title=Dodgers' nicknames for 2018 Players' Weekend|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/dodgers-players-weekend-names-breakdown-c250393424|title=Dodgers' Players Weekend names breakdown|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-mlb-players-nicknames-20170809-story.html|title=MLB players get to wear nicknames on their jerseys for one weekend: So which Dodger is \u2018Dizzy\u2019? Or \u2018Sam\u2019?|last=Schilken|first=Chuck|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.truebluela.com/2018/8/10/17675360/ranking-the-dodgers-2018-players-weekend-nicknames|title=Ranking Players' Weekend Nicknames|last=fbihop|date=2018-08-10|website=True Blue LA|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarnes is the nephew of former MLB infielder [[Mike Gallego]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/2017/07/04/austin-barnes-and-the-tools-of-persistence/|title=Austin Barnes and the tools of persistence|work=Orange County Register|first=Mark|last=Whicker|date=July 4, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> His younger brother, Griffin, played catcher for [[Grand Canyon University]] and recently signed with the [[Los Angeles Angels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gculopes.com/news/2018/6/9/baseball-barnes-signs-with-angels.aspx?path=baseball|title=Barnes signs with the Angels|work=Grand Canyon University|first=Josh|last=Hauser|date=June 11, 2018|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> His favorite actor is [[Will Ferrell]] and he enjoys playing [[golf]] in his free time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thesundevils.com/news/2013/4/17/208245639.aspx|title=Player Profile: Austin Barnes - Arizona State University Official Athletic Site|work=Arizona State University|date=April 17, 2013|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> His birthday is December 28.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Austin Barnes}}\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n{{Baseballstats |mlb=605131 |espn=32856 |br=b/barneau01 |fangraphs=12158|brm=barnes000aus}}\n*[http://www.thesundevils.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30300&ATCLID=208245639 Arizona State Sun Devils bio]\n\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Austin}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Riverside, California]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Arizona State Sun Devils baseball players]]\n[[Category:Jamestown Jammers players]]\n[[Category:Greensboro Grasshoppers players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Suns players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Rancho Cucamonga Quakes players]]\n", "name_user": "Adog", "label": "safe", "comment": "Birthday as sentence is irrelevant", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austin_Barnes"}
